üìò Security Concepts ‚Äì PG-DITISS (Aug 2025)
Session 18: Backdoors, DDoS, Biometric Spoofing, Linux Hacking, IDS/IPS, Honeypots, Firewalls
üîπ BASIC MCQs (10)
1. A backdoor device is used to:
A. Improve authentication
B. Provide hidden access to a system
C. Encrypt traffic
D. Monitor logs

2. Distributed DoS (DDoS) attacks differ from DoS because they use:
A. One system
B. Multiple compromised systems
C. Encryption
D. Firewalls

3. Biometric spoofing involves:
A. Password guessing
B. Faking biometric traits
C. Session hijacking
D. SQL Injection

4. Linux hacking usually targets:
A. Hardware BIOS
B. OS services and configurations
C. Network cables
D. Power supply

5. Linux backdoors allow attackers to:
A. Patch kernel
B. Maintain persistent access
C. Improve security
D. Monitor traffic only

6. IDS stands for:
A. Internet Detection System
B. Intrusion Detection System
C. Internal Defense Software
D. Integrated Data Security

7. Honeypots are used to:
A. Block attackers
B. Detect and study attacker behavior
C. Encrypt data
D. Increase bandwidth

8. Firewalls mainly control:
A. File integrity
B. Network traffic flow
C. Password policies
D. Malware signatures

9. IPS differs from IDS because IPS:
A. Only detects
B. Only logs
C. Can block attacks actively
D. Is offline

10. DMZ is used to:
A. Hide internal servers
B. Separate public-facing services from internal network
C. Encrypt databases
D. Improve performance

üî∏ INTERMEDIATE MCQs (10)
11. Backdoors are MOST dangerous because they:
A. Slow systems
B. Bypass authentication
C. Use encryption
D. Consume CPU

12. DDoS attacks mainly violate which CIA principle?
A. Confidentiality
B. Integrity
C. Availability
D. Authentication

13. Biometric spoofing is possible because biometric systems:
A. Are encrypted
B. Cannot be changed easily
C. Use passwords
D. Are hardware-based

14. Linux privilege escalation exploits:
A. Hardware bugs
B. Misconfigurations and vulnerabilities
C. Network cables
D. Firewalls

15. Linux backdoors commonly use which mechanism?
A. Hidden services or modified binaries
B. Antivirus
C. IDS rules
D. Encryption only

16. An IDS generates:
A. Automatic blocks
B. Alerts and logs
C. Encryption keys
D. Backups

17. Honeypots should be:
A. Same as production servers
B. Isolated from critical systems
C. Fully trusted
D. Internet-facing only

18. Firewalls operate mainly at:
A. Physical layer
B. Network & transport layers
C. Application layer only
D. Data link only

19. IPS is MOST useful for:
A. Forensics
B. Real-time attack prevention
C. Reporting
D. Backup

20. DMZ placement usually includes:
A. User PCs
B. Internal databases
C. Web/mail servers
D. Backup tapes

üî∫ ADVANCED MCQs (10) ‚Äì CCEE TRAP ZONE
21. Why backdoors are harder to detect than malware?
A. Use less bandwidth
B. Appear as legitimate services
C. Are encrypted
D. Use UDP

22. DDoS attacks are difficult to mitigate because:
A. Use TCP only
B. Originate from many locations
C. Are encrypted
D. Use DNS only

23. Biometric spoofing MOST directly affects:
A. Availability
B. Confidentiality
C. Authentication
D. Integrity

24. Linux backdoor persistence is BEST achieved by modifying:
A. User documents
B. Startup scripts / services
C. Firewall rules
D. Log files only

25. Which tool is commonly used as IDS/IPS in labs?
A. Metasploit
B. SNORT
C. Wireshark
D. Nmap

26. Honeypots are intentionally made:
A. Secure
B. Vulnerable
C. Encrypted
D. Invisible

27. Firewalls FAIL to stop attacks when attacks:
A. Use allowed ports
B. Use encryption
C. Are logged
D. Are blocked

28. Difference between IDS and IPS is that IPS:
A. Detects only
B. Alerts only
C. Actively prevents attacks
D. Is offline

29. Using Nagios in lab helps mainly with:
A. Malware creation
B. Monitoring and alerting
C. Packet sniffing
D. Password cracking

30. Session 18 mainly tests understanding of:
A. Programming
B. Infrastructure attacks & defensive controls
C. Database tuning
D. Hardware repair

